const MSG = "REVISE slice-01-run-launcher.dc.html in place (do NOT create a new file, do NOT touch Crucible Design System.dc.html or _palette_notes.md). This is iteration 3. Three persona reviewers raised the following materially-new changes after iteration 2 (items addressed in iter-2 are not re-listed). Apply every one of them where they do not contradict each other; where they contradict, prefer accessibility and audit-posture rules over visual-density rules.\n\nTHESE ARE STATIC HTML MOCKS, not an interactive React app. The reviewers explicitly did NOT flag missing interactivity. Every item below is about static visual, copy, or layout decisions that you can fix in the HTML.\n\n### BANK MODEL RISK OFFICER (SR 11-7 audience) (7 items)\n\n1. ELEMENT: Judge-acknowledgment checkbox in HAPPY state right rail (lines 205-208)\n   ISSUE: The acknowledgment checkbox is rendered pre-checked (filled cyan \u2713 inside a bordered box) in the static HAPPY mockup. For SR 11-7 informed-consent posture, the acknowledgment of a known model limitation must be an affirmative operator action \u2014 pre-checked defaults fail the effective-challenge documentation test because the audit cannot distinguish 'operator read and agreed' from 'operator clicked Start without seeing the disclosure.' Pre-ticked consent UI has been specifically called out by regulators (E.U. Court of Justice Planet49, GAO commentary on attestations) as not constituting acknowledgment.\n   CHANGE: Default the checkbox to UNCHECKED in the HAPPY state mockup. The HAPPY state with Start enabled implies the operator has just checked it \u2014 show the checkbox checked AND show an inline 'acknowledged 14:07:48Z by j.okafor' caption immediately below the checkbox label so the audit trail of the click is visible. The EMPTY state should show the unchecked default. Disable the Start button until the box is checked (currently the visual coupling is implicit).\n\n2. ELEMENT: 'recorded in run-launch payload \u00b7 audit' micro-line under acknowledgment (line 209)\n   ISSUE: The micro-line claims the acknowledgment is captured to the audit trail, but the captured fields (operator id, timestamp, spec sha at moment of acknowledgment, judge-weight value acknowledged) are not enumerated anywhere. A risk officer cannot rely on a claim that 'something gets logged' without knowing the schema. SR 11-7 effective-challenge documentation requires the audit record's shape to be known before the run, not discovered after.\n   CHANGE: Expand the line to a 2-line monospace block: 'audit field: ack.operator=j.okafor \u00b7 ack.ts=14:07:48Z \u00b7 ack.spec_sha=9f2a4c7b \u00b7 ack.judge_weight=1/5' and make 'audit field' a link to the audit-schema documentation. This converts a vague promise into a verifiable contract.\n\n3. ELEMENT: SESSION cost meter monthly cap '$61.40 / $250.00 mo' (lines 58, 255, 386)\n   ISSUE: The per-run dollar ceiling carries a policy reference (MRG-12.3) but the workspace monthly cap of $250.00 is presented as a bare number with no policy reference, no approver, and no indication of what happens when the cap is breached (hard stop? notify? approve-to-continue?). A bank examiner asking 'who set $250 and what governs an override?' has no answer from this surface. The progress bar segment under the cap implies enforcement without naming the enforcement rule.\n   CHANGE: Add a policy reference next to the monthly cap in all three states: '$61.40 / $250.00 mo \u00b7 policy MRG-12.4 \u2197' as a click target, mirroring the per-run treatment. Add a tooltip or footnote naming the enforcement behavior at 100% (e.g., 'hard stop \u00b7 risk-approver override required'). Without this the monthly cap is informational decoration rather than a control.\n\n4. ELEMENT: Inspect drawer RAW RESPONSE / TOKENS / COST chips (lines 538-552)\n   ISSUE: The validator LLM call is inspected but the model identifier and model version are absent. The drawer header names the call as 'SPEC VALIDATOR CALL' but does not say WHICH model made it (claude-3-5-sonnet? gpt-4o? a fine-tuned variant?), its version, its temperature, its system-prompt hash, or its provider. For SR 11-7 traceability every LLM invocation in the audit chain must name the model + version + provider so a future challenger model swap is detectable. The cost figure '$0.008' without a model is unfalsifiable.\n   CHANGE: Add a model-identity strip immediately under the drawer subtitle: 'model: claude-3-5-sonnet-20251022 \u00b7 provider: anthropic \u00b7 temperature: 0.0 \u00b7 system-prompt sha: 4c7b8a9d\u2026 \u00b7 invoked 14:07:47Z'. Make the sha clickable to the prompt-version registry. The token/cost/latency chips at the bottom are fine but become meaningful only with the model identified.\n\n5. ELEMENT: Sandbox environment block in right rail (lines 216-223)\n   ISSUE: The image is identified as 'crucible/sandbox:v1.4.2' \u2014 a mutable tag, not an immutable digest. Container tags can be re-pushed silently; a tag-only reference does not let a risk officer prove which bytes ran. For sealed-evaluation governance the image must be referenced by content digest (sha256:\u2026) so the run is byte-reproducible. Same concern applies to the cost-model 'v2.1' reference in the EST/RUN chip \u2014 version label without commit hash.\n   CHANGE: Show the image as 'crucible/sandbox:v1.4.2@sha256:c4f9a2\u2026' (truncated digest) with the digest as a click target into the registry. The 'model v2.1' reference in the cost chip should likewise show 'cost-model v2.1 \u00b7 commit 4c7b\u2026' as a link (the Estimate drawer already shows the commit; surface it on the chip itself so the audit trail is visible without opening a drawer).\n\n6. ELEMENT: Error-state attempt-id tail (line 404) and Fix & Re-Validate button (line 461)\n   ISSUE: The error tail names attempt id, validator version, and audit-entry path \u2014 good \u2014 but it does not name the operator who submitted the failed attempt. The remediation button 'Fix & Re-Validate' triggers a re-submission with no visible indication of whether the re-submission will be logged as a new attempt id linked to the failed one, or whether it will overwrite. SR 11-7 requires every validation attempt (including failures) to be a discrete, immutable audit record with operator attribution.\n   CHANGE: Extend the attempt-id tail to: 'attempt id: a3f9c2\u2026 \u00b7 operator: j.okafor \u00b7 validator: spec-validator-v1.4 \u00b7 audit entry: /audit/attempts/a3f9c2 \u2197 \u00b7 parent of: <next attempt>'. Adjacent to the Fix & Re-Validate button, add a small monospace caption: 'creates new attempt id linked to a3f9c2 \u00b7 previous attempt remains immutable in audit log.'\n\n7. ELEMENT: Three-state composite layout (states stacked under labeled HAPPY/EMPTY/ERROR separator chips at lines 31, 231, 362)\n   ISSUE: Iter-01 already flagged the composite-page concern. Iter-02 preserves the composite structure unchanged \u2014 same three colored separator chips, same stacked vertical arrangement. Calling this out again only to acknowledge the iter-01 item is unresolved; the page still reads as a design-system comp rather than the live operator route. The separator labels even still say 'HAPPY \u2014 valid spec, budget set, target picked, judge acknowledged' which is design-comp vocabulary, not operator-facing copy.\n   CHANGE: (Carryover, restated only because iter-01's resolution did not land.) Split into three separate artifact files (v2-happy.html, v2-empty.html, v2-error.html) so each screenshot is indistinguishable from the live route. The labeled separators are the most visible giveaway that this is a comp.\n\n### CODE-GEN AGENT VENDOR ENGINEERING LEAD (GitHub Dark / Linear / Vercel) (5 items)\n\n1. ELEMENT: Top-right cost meter, 'how this is estimated \u24d8' link inside the EST/RUN column\n   ISSUE: The estimate column now stacks four lines of text (label, value, timestamp+model, and an underlined help link), which crowds the primary scalar that operators glance at from a second monitor. The new 'as of 14:07:52Z \u00b7 model v2.1' line and the underlined 'how this is estimated \u24d8' affordance both sit at 9px directly under the $8.40, so the eye has to skip a small-print band to land on the value, and a second underlined link competes with the 'ledger \u25be' button beside it. Vercel/Linear keep the persistent top-right meter at exactly one value + one label; secondary metadata lives in the drawer the chip opens.\n   CHANGE: Remove the inline 'as of \u2026' and 'how this is estimated \u24d8' lines from inside the EST/RUN column. Keep only the label ('EST / RUN'), the value ($8.40), and rely on the existing 'ledger \u25be' affordance (or a single click on the value) to open the estimate drawer where the timestamp, cost-model version, and formula already live. Mirror the same simplification on the SESSION column \u2014 the 'as of 14:07:52Z' belongs in the drawer.\n\n2. ELEMENT: Right-rail RUN SUMMARY 'Est. spend' value '$8.40 \u2013 $25.00' painted in #57C08A (success green)\n   ISSUE: Spend forecasts should not be colored green. Green in this palette is reserved for positive verdicts (\u2713 sealed \u00b7 valid, \u2713 within policy, \u2713 preserved). Painting the dollar range green semantically reads as 'this is the good outcome,' but the operator's job at this row is to read the numeric range neutrally and decide whether to lower the ceiling. Datadog/Sentry render numeric forecasts in body color and reserve the success hue for status verdicts.\n   CHANGE: Render '$8.40 \u2013 $25.00' in the standard body color (#E8EDF3) at the same mono treatment as the Rounds / Oracles values directly above it. Keep #57C08A exclusively for status verdicts (the '\u2713 within policy' line, the '\u2713 sealed \u00b7 valid' pill, etc.).\n\n3. ELEMENT: Right-rail BUDGET CONSUMED ruler in the happy state ($0.00 / $25.00, 0% filled)\n   ISSUE: On the launcher (pre-start), the budget ruler always reads 0 / $25.00 with an empty bar because no spend has accrued yet \u2014 the run hasn't started. A meter that always shows zero on this screen is chrome with no signal; it teaches the operator's eye to ignore the ruler before they ever see it carry data on the live-run view. The 'as of HH:MM:SSZ' rule applies here too: a zero with no run context is the same failure mode as a $0.00 placeholder estimate, which the empty-state correctly avoids with the 'Not yet measured' tile.\n   CHANGE: Drop the BUDGET CONSUMED ruler from the launcher (happy state). Replace it with a single mono line: 'consumed \u00b7 \u2014 / $25.00 (run not started)'. The ruler belongs on the live-run view where it carries a live value. If the ruler must stay for layout reasons, render it with no fill segment and a 'starts at launch' caption so it does not read as a real measurement.\n\n4. ELEMENT: Error-state remediation checklist, step 3 ('Re-seal, then start')\n   ISSUE: The three-step list collapses two distinct operator actions ('Re-seal' and 'then start') into one numbered step, which breaks the contract the rest of the checklist sets up (one verb per step). An operator scanning the list under pressure will tick step 3 after re-sealing and miss that Start is a separate decision \u2014 exactly the kind of error this remediation panel exists to prevent. Linear's blocker checklists keep one verb per row so the eye can match action-to-checkbox.\n   CHANGE: Split step 3 into two rows: '3. Re-seal the spec' and '4. Start evaluation'. Keep the same numbered-circle treatment. Optionally render step 4 in muted text (#7C8896 with the circle in #2C3744) until steps 1\u20133 are complete, so the operator sees Start as the explicit final action, not a clause.\n\n5. ELEMENT: Empty-state 'NotYetMeasured' tile body copy ('No estimate until a target and budget are set \u2014 never a $0.00 placeholder.')\n   ISSUE: The trailing clause '\u2014 never a $0.00 placeholder' is meta-commentary about the design rule (no fake/stub data), addressed at the design reviewer rather than at the operator looking at the screen. Operators reading this don't need to know what the tile is NOT doing; they need to know what they must do next. This is the same anti-pattern as rationalizing copy ('hence green', 'older format') the project guidance explicitly calls out.\n   CHANGE: Rewrite the body to be operator-facing only: 'No estimate yet. Pick a target, paste a spec, and set a budget \u2014 the estimate will appear here.' Remove the '\u2014 never a $0.00 placeholder' clause. The no-stub-data rule should be invisible to the user; it's only visible when violated.\n\n### PUBLIC-SECTOR AI PROCUREMENT OFFICER (WCAG, NIST audience) (5 items)\n\n1. ELEMENT: Muted label color #7C8896 on background #0E141B used pervasively for form labels ('TARGET ADAPTER', 'EVALUATION BUDGET', 'RUN SUMMARY', 'SANDBOX ENVIRONMENT'), step counters ('step 1 of 3'), the 'Rounds' / 'Dollar ceiling' sub-labels, and every workspace-chrome timestamp line\n   ISSUE: Computed contrast ratio is approximately 4.4:1 (foreground luminance ~0.222, background luminance ~0.0073). That fails the WCAG AA floor of 4.5:1 for normal body text. Because this is the dominant 'chrome' color of the whole launcher \u2014 every section header, every metadata line, every step counter \u2014 a low-vision colleague or a procurement reviewer squint-testing on a 24-inch monitor at modest brightness loses the entire information scaffolding of the screen. WCAG AAA (7:1) is the bar this persona rewards and the current value is not even AA.\n   CHANGE: Promote the muted-label color from #7C8896 to at least #95A1AE on #0E141B (\u22485.6:1, AA pass) or, to also clear AAA for the screen-reading colleagues, #AAB5C2 (\u22487.2:1). Apply the lift everywhere #7C8896 currently sits on the page background, including 'EST / RUN', 'SESSION', 'BUDGET CONSUMED', 'as of HH:MM:SSZ', 'step N of 3', and YAML line numbers.\n\n2. ELEMENT: Cost-meter timestamp lines 'as of 14:07:52Z \u00b7 model v2.1' and 'no estimate yet' / 'blocked \u00b7 spec invalid', plus the inline 'how this is estimated \u24d8' link, all rendered at 9 px and 10 px in the top chrome\n   ISSUE: The persona's standing rule is 'type readable at smaller sizes \u2014 14 pixel base must remain legible'. Rendering critical provenance (the timestamp that proves the estimate is fresh, the model version that proves which cost model produced it) and an actionable link ('how this is estimated') at 9 px and 10 px breaks that floor by a wide margin. At 9 px on a 24-inch monitor the timestamp is effectively decorative; the operator has to lean in to read the proof of freshness, which defeats the purpose of showing it.\n   CHANGE: Raise every cost-meter metadata line, the 'as of \u2026Z' timestamps, and the 'how this is estimated' affordance to at least 12 px (and preferably 13 px to match the rest of the run-summary rail). If horizontal space is tight, drop the 'model v2.1' suffix to a second line rather than shrinking the type.\n\n3. ELEMENT: 'Rounds' and 'Dollar ceiling' inputs in the EMPTY state \u2014 placeholder text 'e.g. 48' and 'e.g. $25.00' rendered with the browser default placeholder color\n   ISSUE: No explicit placeholder color is set on the inputs, so browsers fall back to their default placeholder grey (Chrome/Safari ~ #757575 at ~54 % opacity, Firefox similar). On the #0E141B input background that lands well under AA 4.5:1. The placeholder is the only on-screen hint of the expected format ('e.g. 48' for rounds, '$25.00' with the dollar sign for ceiling), so under-contrast placeholder kills the format guidance for low-vision operators.\n   CHANGE: Add an explicit '::placeholder { color:#95A1AE; opacity:1; }' rule (or inline equivalent) for the launcher inputs so the placeholder hits AA on #0E141B, and pair the placeholder with a small persistent helper line below each input ('integer \u00b7 capped at workspace round-budget', 'USD \u00b7 capped at workspace ceiling $25.00') so the format guidance is not lost when the field receives focus and the placeholder disappears.\n\n4. ELEMENT: Top-chrome 'SSE connected' status indicator (green dot at #57C08A with text label) present and identical across all three states \u2014 HAPPY, EMPTY, and the ERROR state where the YAML failed to parse\n   ISSUE: In the error state the same green 'SSE connected' indicator sits in the chrome while a red 'PARSE ERROR' banner sits directly below it. A procurement reviewer scanning the masthead sees a green health pip and may parse the page as 'system healthy' before reading downward. The 'connected' vocabulary also overloads two different ideas (transport health vs. run health) under one green status, with no in-line definition of what 'SSE' refers to. The persona bar requires iconography paired with plain-language labels; 'SSE' is a three-letter acronym with no gloss on screen.\n   CHANGE: Expand 'SSE connected' to a plain-language phrasing such as 'Live updates \u00b7 connected' (or 'Event stream \u00b7 connected') and add a small adjacent text link 'about live updates' that opens a one-paragraph definition. Independently, when a higher-severity banner is present (parse error, sealed-spec failure, budget over policy), demote the transport-health pip from green to neutral grey-with-checkmark so it cannot be mistaken for an all-clear on the run itself.\n\n5. ELEMENT: YAML viewer in the HAPPY state \u2014 boolean `true` values on lines 3, 6, 10 rendered in #57C08A green as the only differentiator from surrounding plain text\n   ISSUE: The truthiness of the obligation values is conveyed by color alone. WCAG 1.4.1 'Use of Color' requires that color not be the sole means of conveying information. A procurement reviewer using a high-contrast or grayscale screen-reader profile loses the cue that 'metamorphic.invariance == true' and 'enabled: true' are the affirmative settings the run depends on.\n   CHANGE: Pair every color-coded YAML value with a non-color glyph or weight cue \u2014 for example bold the keyword `true` in addition to the green color, or render it as 'true \u2713' inline. Apply the same rule to the green '\u2713 sealed \u00b7 valid' badge by keeping both the glyph and a text label ('sealed and valid') and never relying on the color swap alone.\n\nAfter applying these changes, the file should still be one HTML file at slice-01-run-launcher.dc.html with the three stacked states (happy, empty, error). Keep mounting the Crucible Design System components and palette; do not introduce new colors. Reply with a one-line summary of which items you applied and which you intentionally did not (with one-clause reason each).";
const input = document.querySelector('.ProseMirror[contenteditable="true"]');
if (!input) { JSON.stringify({err: 'no-input'}); }
else {
  input.focus();
  document.execCommand('selectAll');
  document.execCommand('delete');
  document.execCommand('insertText', false, MSG);
  void (async () => {
    await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 500));
  })();
  const sendBtn = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('button')).find(b => /^send$/i.test((b.textContent || '').trim()));
  JSON.stringify({
    insertedChars: input.innerText.length,
    firstWords: input.innerText.slice(0, 80),
    sendFound: !!sendBtn,
    sendDisabled: sendBtn ? (sendBtn.disabled || sendBtn.getAttribute('aria-disabled') === 'true') : null,
  });
}
